<div class="comment-wrapper"><ul class="comments"><li class="comment"><div class="avatar"><img src="https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d53b7c5f9b5f5557b9082face9b632a0?s=50"></div><header><strong>changes in the inliner</strong> from <string>Dave Abrahams</string> &lt;dabrahams at apple.com&gt;<p>April  6, 2016 at 10:00:00am</p></header><div class="content"><p>on Fri Apr 01 2016, Erik Eckstein &lt;swift-dev-AT-swift.org&gt; wrote:<br></p><p>&gt; Hi,<br>&gt;<br>&gt; I&#39;d like to give some more information about the inliner changes I landed this week.<br>&gt;<br>&gt; The goal was to restrict inlining to improve code size while not degrade performance (too much).<br>&gt; This was mainly achieved by improving the heuristic for the inlining decisions.<br>&gt; Some of our optimizations are still not as inlining-indepenent as we<br>&gt; want them to be. Therefore I had to do some fine-tuning in the stdlib<br>&gt; (e.g. with the new onFastPath builtin).<br>&gt; There are a few minor regressions, but overall performance looks ok.<br>&gt;<br>&gt; The code size reductions are approximately:<br>&gt; stdlib: 3%<br>&gt; Benchmarks_O: 9%<br>&gt; Two larger applications: 15%, 20%<br></p><p>That&#39;s HUGE, Erik!  Great work.<br></p><p>-- <br>Dave<br></p></div></li></ul></div>    </main>
